June 22 @jillsobule makes her way to the CSPS Hall stage for a night that will entertain, amuse, and provoke.  Learn more and secure your advance tickets at https://cspshall.org/jill-sobule.

The Denver-born songwriter/guitarist/singer's work is at once deeply personal and socially conscious, seriously funny and derisively tragic. While her songs cover expansive thematic ground, they benefit greatly from Jill's subtle intelligence and skillful light-handedness. No sloganeering flag and fist waving here, but rather portrait and story songs about human beings, real and imagined, which allow us to step back from the issues they tackle, be they individual or societal, and to relate to them as we would a close friend.
Songwriting classes in August. Learn to write hit  songs. You can quit your job, hobnob backstage with Broadway stars, and become a happy alcoholic for a time

JILL SOBULE (COURTYARD SHOW)
Wednesday, June 21
5PM DOORS // 6PM SHOWTIME

$25 ADVANCE // $30 DAY OF SHOW

“Jill Sobule can claim her place among the stellar New York singer-songwriters of the last decade. Topical, funny and more than a little poignant …grown-up music for an adolescent age.” - @nytimes

@jillsobule’s work is at once deeply personal and socially conscious, seriously funny and derisively tragic. In a dozen albums spanning three decades of recording, the Denver-born songwriter/guitarist/singer has tackled such topics as the death penalty, anorexia nervosa, shoplifting, reproduction, the French Resistance, adolescent malaise, LGBTQ issues, and the Christian Right. Her hits include “I Kissed A Girl”—the first openly gay-themed song ever to crack the Billboard Top 20—and the alt-rock anthem “Supermodel” featured in the film “Clueless”.

Full food and beverage menu available at your table.

A bunch of people have hired me to sing one song on my iPhone and personalize it. So far a few request for trains - seems to be a big one. And a couple of Kissed a Girls - corny and all. For the best holiday gift ever! And a swell deal as I love doing it! You can message me!

Christmas is the Saddest Day of the Year. Was #9 of the most depressing holiday songs according to to Entertainment Weekly. Right above William S. Burroughs’s “The Junky’s Christmas. I’m very proud. Recorded on a 4-track Tascam cassette machine.
Stevie Wonder in the studio with the Synth wiz duo TONTO (“The Original New Timbral Orchestra.”). I didn’t realize how important they were to the sound.

Today, I sang (on the iPhone video) our personalized "Trains", five "Karen By Night", and an "I Kissed a Girl" where I sang "I Kissed Heather Miller" - no shame. Oh, and someone gifted my classic breakup song "Now, That I Don't Have You". That doesn't seem right, but whatever makes someone happy. If you want a song -email jill@jillsobule.com and one of the operators will give you all the info.
